<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="Incline-Barbell-Bench-Press">Incline Barbell Bench Press</h3>



<p>The incline barbell bench press uses the foundational pressing movement. However, it performs it on an incline. This shifts the focus to the clavicular heads (closer to the collar bone) of the pectoralis major and anterior deltoids.&nbsp;</p>



<p>The primary movers are the clavicular heads of the <a href="https://www.researchgate.net/publication/335136115_A_Detailed_Review_on_the_Clinical_Anatomy_of_the_Pectoralis_Major_Muscle" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">pectoralis major</a>. The secondary muscles are the anterior deltoids, triceps brachii, serratus anterior, and other heads of the pectoralis major.&nbsp;</p>



<p>Like the bench press, the incline bench press develops a functional movement pattern. It&#8217;s a great pressing exercise that works most of the upper body musculature.</p>



<figure class="wp-block-embed is-type-video is-provider-vimeo wp-block-embed-vimeo wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio vimeo-custom"><div class="wp-block-embed__wrapper">
