<h2 class="wp-block-heading info-heading">Shoulder Anatomy At A Glance</h2>



<p>The <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1323385/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">shoulder</a> includes bones and joints. The three main bones are the clavicle, scapula, and humerus. The clavicle links the arm to the chest and attaches to different muscles that link it to the neck, shoulder blades,&nbsp; chest, and arm.</p>



<p>The scapula attaches to the body through muscles. This scapula consists of a bony component that attaches to the clavicle. The humerus bone, whose top has a spherical portion, is a socket for the spatula.</p>



<p>The three joints are glenohumeral, which connects the humerus to the scapula; acromioclavicular (links the clavicle to the scapula); and sternavicular (joins the clavicle to the sternum).</p>



<p>Moreover, the shoulder has intrinsic and extrinsic muscles. The intrinsic muscles run from the scapula to the humerus. These muscles include the trapezius, latissimus dorsi, levator scapulae, rhomboid major, and rhomboid minor.</p>



<p>For example, when performing push-press workouts, several muscles get affected. First, the movements from these workouts activate rhomboids to stabilize the scapula. When you lift the barbell, trapezius muscles develop for a stable neck and shoulder. Lastly, this push-press exercise strengthens deltoid muscles that stabilize the shoulder.</p>


